00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:27.840
And then we'll get into
the good conversation.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:30.120
So, obviously, when we're
talking about identity

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:33.820
for folks, it encompasses all
kinds of things for all of us,

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:34.320
right?

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:37.410
And our gender identity,
the sex that we

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:40.470
are assigned at birth, our
sexual orientation, all

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:43.890
of those are components
of who we are as a whole.

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:45.450
Goes without saying, kind of.

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:47.880
But I mention it here
because particularly

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.310
in the systems that
we're talking about,

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:53.580
overwhelmingly it's
young people of color

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.190
that are represented in these
out-of-home care systems,

00:03:56.190 --> 00:03:58.110
like foster care and
juvenile justice,

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:01.740
because of social
justice issues,

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:04.410
institutional racism,
all kinds of things

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:07.590
that drive young people of color
into those systems at higher

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:09.510
rates, right?

00:04:09.510 --> 00:04:11.700
So when we're talking
about the young people

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:14.520
that I'm going to be going over
and talking about their rights

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:17.940
today, really we're
talking about queer trans

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:18.850
youth of color.

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:20.308
That's who we're
talking about, OK?

00:04:20.308 --> 00:04:23.070
So that's why I wanted to put
this on, a slide up, so you

00:04:23.070 --> 00:04:25.457
can think about kind
of people holistically,

00:04:25.457 --> 00:04:27.540
even though we're going
to be specifically talking

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:30.640
about sexual orientation and
gender identity, sex, and all

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.230
that today.

00:04:32.230 --> 00:04:38.010
So there's not nearly enough
data about how LGBTQ+ young

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:41.490
people are doing in these
systems because it's really

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:42.975
difficult, for
important reasons,

00:04:42.975 --> 00:04:45.300
not to be doing research on
children and particularly

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:46.800
children that are
in custody, right?

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:49.500
But we do know some things, OK?

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.680
So part of this data I've
kind of summarized here

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:55.860
in this chart, which is
kind of this vicious cycle

00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:57.790
that a lot of
LGBTQ young people,

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:00.990
particularly young people of
color, get into, all right?

00:05:00.990 --> 00:05:03.897
And that is if you've
been rejected from home

00:05:03.897 --> 00:05:06.480
because of who you are-- so your
parents have literally kicked

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:10.170
you out, which happens to way
too many LGBTQ+ young people,

00:05:10.170 --> 00:05:10.800
right--

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:13.980
then you can go directly to
experiencing homelessness.

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.040
Or you might be picked up by
the foster care system, placed

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:18.900
into foster care.

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:20.850
If you're not treated
well in foster care

00:05:20.850 --> 00:05:22.800
and are running away
from a foster home that

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:24.420
isn't supportive
of you, then you

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:26.460
could go from there
to homelessness.

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:29.160
Or if you have a conflict
with your foster parent

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:31.170
because they don't
like who you are

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:34.500
or the way you present, and
you get into a fight in school

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.430
or at home, and then
get an assault charge,

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:40.320
then you can go over to the
juvenile justice system.

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.350
Or if you're in a school
and you're being bullied--

00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:45.990
and Lydia will talk a
little bit about this,

00:05:45.990 --> 00:05:48.960
right-- then you can
go straight from school

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:50.830
into the juvenile
justice system.

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:52.590
How many of you have
seen "Moonlight?"

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:53.120
All righty.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:53.620
Right?

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:55.980
There's a really, like, just--

00:05:55.980 --> 00:05:58.590
scene there that really
hits home, right,

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:01.080
of Chiron being
picked on in school,

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:02.932
and then he gets
arrested and hauled off

00:06:02.932 --> 00:06:04.890
because he's fighting
back for being picked on.

00:06:04.890 --> 00:06:07.030
So that's kind of what
we're talking about here.

00:06:07.030 --> 00:06:08.880
And I have additional
factors on there

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:11.940
to think about other aspects
of identity and who you are,

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:14.850
particularly thinking about
if you're undocumented.

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:17.100
And all of this is kind
of happening, right?

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:20.910
Like the additional layers of
challenges that you may face.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:22.830
And, unfortunately,
this cycle happens

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:24.960
for a lot of young people.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.110
But for LGBTQ+ youth, and
particularly those of color,

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:29.325
this is, like, on steroids.

00:06:29.325 --> 00:06:31.200
So you're going from
one system to the other,

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:33.540
you are multi systemic
involved, and also

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:37.650
if you're in foster care and
you haven't been affirmed there,

00:06:37.650 --> 00:06:40.820
then that can lead to sort
of all of these other things,

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:43.820
and then sort of
back in again, right?

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:47.540
So just important to think about
the different layers of system

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:51.110
involvement, kind of the reasons
why and that this cycle happens

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.500
at elevated rates for
LGBTQ+ young people.

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:55.130
OK.

00:06:55.130 --> 00:06:58.310
So people always want to
know what the numbers are.

00:06:58.310 --> 00:07:00.050
Like, what are we talking about?

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:01.610
That, again, as I
said earlier, is

00:07:01.610 --> 00:07:04.580
challenging because we don't
necessarily have enough data.

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:08.960
But what we do have is a study
out of Los Angeles County that

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:13.400
basically found that out of
this 700+ young people they

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:18.950
surveyed, 19.1%
identified as LGBTQ.

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:23.660
So that's over double, probably,
than our estimates of LGBTQ+

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:25.980
people in the
general population.

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:31.310
And then if you look at this one
circle with transgender youth,

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:35.120
the survey came out with 5.6%
of the young people surveyed

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:38.510
identifying as trans, which,
if our estimates are maybe

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:43.400
1% to 2% of people in
general identifying as trans,

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:45.860
that's enormous
over-representation.

00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:48.710
So kind of going back
to our, like, why

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:50.630
are those numbers so high?

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:53.192
So much of it is fueled
by family rejection.

00:07:53.192 --> 00:07:55.650
So, kids getting kicked out
and ending up in these systems,

00:07:55.650 --> 00:07:58.100
even though they may end up
for other reasons, that's

00:07:58.100 --> 00:07:59.570
largely what's fueling it.

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:02.030
In the juvenile justice system,
the numbers are the same.

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:03.260
20%.

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:04.970
I mean, one study in
Northern California

00:08:04.970 --> 00:08:08.390
recently, about 30% of girls
who are in the juvenile justice

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:10.850
system in California
identified somewhere

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:12.690
along the LGBTQ spectrum.

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:15.620
So we're talking about a way
over-representation, which

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:18.980
is why Lambda has this youth in
out-of-home care project that I

00:08:18.980 --> 00:08:21.194
focus on, which is
because there's so

00:08:21.194 --> 00:08:22.610
many young people
in these systems

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:25.190
and we know that they have
really bad experiences there,

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:26.720
many of them, OK?

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.440
So this also leads to this
criminalization factor

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:33.049
I was talking about when
I alluded to "Moonlight."

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:34.880
But there are all kinds
of other pipelines.

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:37.460
How many of you heard of the
school-to-prison pipeline?

00:08:37.460 --> 00:08:38.929
Heard that term before?

00:08:38.929 --> 00:08:42.200
That's one that justifiably
gets a lot of attention

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:43.309
and conversation.

00:08:43.309 --> 00:08:44.700
But there are other pipelines.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:46.910
So I mentioned the foster
care prison pipeline.

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:49.277
So conflict in a group
home, if you're placed there

00:08:49.277 --> 00:08:51.110
with other peers who
aren't accepting of you

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:53.060
or staff who aren't
accepting of you,

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:55.600
can lead to an assault
charge that gets you in jail.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:57.300
Youth who are
experiencing homelessness

00:08:57.300 --> 00:09:01.310
who may be engaging in what some
people call survival crimes.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:04.220
So, for example, you
are engaging in sex work

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:06.830
because you have to pay
for a place to sleep.

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:10.250
Or you're experiencing
homelessness, don't have a job,

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:12.309
and you need to access
public transportation.

00:09:12.309 --> 00:09:13.100
I live in New York.

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.159
So you jump the
subway turnstile,

00:09:15.159 --> 00:09:17.450
and then you get picked up,
and then you get a warrant,

00:09:17.450 --> 00:09:20.075
and then you don't have money to
pay the warrant, and that sort

00:09:20.075 --> 00:09:21.470
of cycle starts, right?

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:25.160
And then the bottom one
we have is walking while.

00:09:25.160 --> 00:09:27.560
So you may have heard people
talk about being picked up

00:09:27.560 --> 00:09:30.050
and walking while black or
driving while black, right?

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:32.690
So for, say, trans
women of color

00:09:32.690 --> 00:09:36.140
are often profiled as engaging
in sex work or prostitution

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:38.510
or just picked up walking
down the street, right?

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:40.940
Because of profiling by police.

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:46.430
So, for example, if you are an
African-American transgender

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:49.790
woman of color in the
foster care system living

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:53.120
in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, for
example, one of my clients,

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:55.250
you could have all of
these things happening

00:09:55.250 --> 00:09:59.300
to you simultaneously or in
different aspects of your life.

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:01.070
So just thinking
about all the factors

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:03.920
that kind of drive young people
into these systems at higher

00:10:03.920 --> 00:10:05.000
numbers.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.650
The foster care
system is one that's

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:08.660
kind of surprising
for folks that ends up

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:11.390
having youth experiencing
homelessness because you think,

00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:13.550
well, isn't that the point
of being in foster care

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:15.350
is that you have
a place to live?

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:18.000
And you have someone who will
adopt you or care for you?

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.780
But, unfortunately, in
the foster care system,

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:23.990
if you don't have people
working to help you get back

00:10:23.990 --> 00:10:27.350
with your family, to help them
understand you and accept you,

00:10:27.350 --> 00:10:28.940
then you can end up
in a foster home.

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:31.460
If the foster home doesn't
accept you for who you are--

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:32.990
and we'll hear
from Savannah talk

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:34.910
a little bit about
that in a minute--

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:37.310
then you can end up in a
shelter or a group home.

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:39.260
If that's not
supportive, then you

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:42.080
can take off, because you
don't feel safe there.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:45.050
And then you can end up homeless
and with no adult connected

00:10:45.050 --> 00:10:47.820
to you outside the system.

00:10:47.820 --> 00:10:51.530
So all of this stuff leads to
this really shocking figure,

00:10:51.530 --> 00:10:54.000
which is 40%.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.450
And that is estimates
of youth who

00:10:56.450 --> 00:10:58.100
are experiencing
homelessness that

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:02.660
identify in the LGBTQ spectrum,
which again, if we think

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:05.570
about maybe 7% to
10% being the numbers

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:07.490
in the general
population, that's

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:11.600
just crazy over-representation
for all of these factors

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:13.304
I talked about.

00:11:13.304 --> 00:11:15.470
And then for young people
that are in these systems,

00:11:15.470 --> 00:11:18.680
once they're in, all
kinds of problems

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:20.270
can happen and do happen.

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:24.710
So one is just not feeling
safe to say who you are.

00:11:24.710 --> 00:11:27.290
So not being able
to come out or talk

00:11:27.290 --> 00:11:30.350
about your sexual orientation
or identity or express yourself

00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:32.450
freely leads to
isolation, which causes

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:34.670
a lot of bad
outcomes, depression,

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:37.130
suicidal ideation,
those sorts of things.

00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:38.480
Being victimized.

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:41.475
So Lydia is going to talk a
little bit about her experience

00:11:41.475 --> 00:11:43.960
in the juvenile justice
facility and being

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:46.960
a victim of assault in
there because of who she is.

00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:48.040
Differential treatment.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:51.520
So, say, straight kids
are allowed to date

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:56.290
and have friends over, have sort
of normal relationships, right,

00:11:56.290 --> 00:11:59.710
but a foster parent may
not allow a young person

00:11:59.710 --> 00:12:02.097
to have a same-sex friend over
that they're attracted to,

00:12:02.097 --> 00:12:02.930
or things like that.

00:12:02.930 --> 00:12:05.100
So different rules applying.

00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:06.670
And then these
disclosure dilemmas

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:08.320
are confidentiality violations.

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.290
So if you do say
who you are, lots

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:13.870
of things you have
to navigate around,

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:16.300
whether it's safe to do that,
how that's going to play,

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:19.270
are you going to be
rejected once you come out.

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:20.480
Confidentiality.

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:24.130
So if you do say who
you are, do people

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:25.710
gossip about that
to somebody else?

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:28.590
Are you outed to other
people without you knowing?

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.340
And then I mentioned
earlier, kind of lack

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:32.000
of family-centered services.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.300
So the foster care
system is supposed

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:37.960
to help you get safely back
to your parents if you can.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:40.210
But if no one's actually
working with your parents

00:12:40.210 --> 00:12:42.830
on accepting you
for who you are,

00:12:42.830 --> 00:12:45.940
then you're already cycling
further into the system,

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:46.906
like we talked about.

00:12:46.906 --> 00:12:48.280
And then, finally,
and a big one,

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:52.240
is the lack of cultural
competency in serving

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:54.430
LGBT youth in these systems.

00:12:54.430 --> 00:12:57.730
So a big example is if you're
a transgender young person

00:12:57.730 --> 00:13:00.760
and you're referred to a
doctor or medical provider who

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.670
knows nothing about working
with trans young people,

00:13:03.670 --> 00:13:05.860
then you're not going to
get accurate information

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:08.770
about whether you may be able
to begin hormone therapy,

00:13:08.770 --> 00:13:11.890
if you're a younger
person, if you're eligible

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:14.800
or a good candidate for
puberty blockers, right?

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.600
You're not getting
accurate information.

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:19.900
For some of my gay
clients in foster care,

00:13:19.900 --> 00:13:22.360
no one has ever mentioned
to them about PrEP,

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:23.920
or the possibility
of being on PrEP,

00:13:23.920 --> 00:13:27.760
so you're really kind of having
to navigate all of these things

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:29.350
within the context
of health care.

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:30.766
And so you're not
actually getting

00:13:30.766 --> 00:13:33.746
your needs met, or accurate
information when you're there.

00:13:33.746 --> 00:13:35.620
So, real quickly, I'll
talk just a little bit

00:13:35.620 --> 00:13:37.487
about the more boring parts.

00:13:37.487 --> 00:13:39.820
Since I'm a lawyer, I feel
obligated to talk about this,

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:41.980
which is the law
and policies that

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:44.170
protects young people
in these systems, right?

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:47.570
So you have constitutional
rights if you're in care.

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:49.340
You have the right
to be treated fairly.

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:50.860
So, to equal protection.

00:13:50.860 --> 00:13:53.770
You also have the right to due
process, which means safety.

00:13:53.770 --> 00:13:55.550
Your physical and
emotional safety.

00:13:55.550 --> 00:13:58.180
So if the state has taken
you away from your parents

00:13:58.180 --> 00:14:00.190
and placed you out
of home, then they

00:14:00.190 --> 00:14:03.340
have an obligation to
ensure that you're safe.

00:14:03.340 --> 00:14:06.400
So every kid in care
has these rights.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.860
Additionally, there
are federal statutes

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:11.030
that provide protection
for discrimination.

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:13.690
So on the juvenile justice
side, the Juvenile Justice

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:16.150
and Delinquency Prevention
Act prohibits discrimination

00:14:16.150 --> 00:14:17.680
based on sex.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:20.950
So we'll talk a little bit
about sex-based discrimination.

00:14:20.950 --> 00:14:22.690
But more and more
courts are saying,

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:28.100
no, sex as a protected class
includes sex stereotyping.

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:31.050
So assuming that men
should be dating women

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:32.440
and marrying women, right?

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.219
Or that you should be conforming
to some sort of expectations

00:14:35.219 --> 00:14:37.510
for the sex that you were
assigned at birth and the way

00:14:37.510 --> 00:14:38.830
you present yourself.

00:14:38.830 --> 00:14:40.990
And also gender identity, right?

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:44.194
Clearly, obviously
connected with sex, right?

00:14:44.194 --> 00:14:45.610
So there may be
protections there.

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:46.750
Regulations.

00:14:46.750 --> 00:14:48.460
At the end of the
Obama administration,

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:50.920
a couple of major
regulations came out

00:14:50.920 --> 00:14:52.820
that provide
explicit protection.

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:55.120
So they say you may
not discriminate

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.070
based on sexual orientation,
gender identity,

00:14:57.070 --> 00:14:59.590
and gender expression
for youth that

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:01.990
are being served by
homeless shelters that

00:15:01.990 --> 00:15:04.330
receive federal funding.

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:06.749
So that is fantastic, right?

00:15:06.749 --> 00:15:08.290
But those are some
of the things that

00:15:08.290 --> 00:15:10.330
are at risk with this
current administration

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:11.380
and current Congress.

00:15:11.380 --> 00:15:15.850
So those are regulations that
they may pull back completely,

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:17.890
cut out through the
Congressional Review Act,

00:15:17.890 --> 00:15:20.380
or try to go through
the regulatory process

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:22.470
to get rid of those.

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:23.980
On the foster care
side, a big one

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:26.290
came out that said if you
receive federal funding

00:15:26.290 --> 00:15:28.020
from Health and
Human Services, then

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:30.790
you can't discriminate based on
sexual orientation and gender

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:31.330
identities.

00:15:31.330 --> 00:15:33.532
That includes child
welfare agencies, right?

00:15:33.532 --> 00:15:34.990
And under the Obama
administration,

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:37.281
a lot of the federal agencies
that look at these things

00:15:37.281 --> 00:15:39.760
did a lot of great
work around LGBTQ.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:43.080
So all that stuff is
absolutely at risk

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.130
now and what we have
to be vigilant about.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:49.120
So from state to state, each
state systems in these areas

00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:50.740
may have explicit protections.

00:15:50.740 --> 00:15:54.100
So probably to the
surprise of no one,

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:57.040
the top two states in
terms of adding protection

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:00.910
for kids in these areas are
New York and California.

00:16:00.910 --> 00:16:03.976
The bottom two, which have no
explicit protection, including

00:16:03.976 --> 00:16:06.100
sexual orientation, gender
identity, or expression,

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:09.250
or even sex in their laws
applicable to these systems

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:12.960
are Alaska and North
Carolina, which as we know,

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.870
North Carolina is already not
doing good things with HB2

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:18.640
in their bill, which
we are litigating

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:21.160
with the ACLU against them.

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:24.010
Also some public accommodation
laws and human rights laws

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:26.350
may protect kids.

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:27.520
So I want to--

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:30.430
I'll show you a quick map
of this and then I'll close.

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:32.530
But I do want to
emphasize particularly

00:16:32.530 --> 00:16:37.210
that transgender youth who
are involved in these systems

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:40.950
really bear the brunt of
a ton of discrimination

00:16:40.950 --> 00:16:44.400
around who they are, from the
basics of not respecting name

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:47.250
and pronouns to not
getting qualified care.

00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:50.370
Like I said, being
placed, if you are a girl,

00:16:50.370 --> 00:16:52.680
being placed in a
boy's group home

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.720
because they interpret
the requirement

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:58.050
to place youth of different
genders in different facilities

00:16:58.050 --> 00:17:02.010
as gender assigned at birth
rather than who you really are.

00:17:02.010 --> 00:17:05.670
So because all of these
systems are so sex-segregated,

00:17:05.670 --> 00:17:09.000
trans youth, or youth who
don't conform with expectations

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:10.470
of their gender
assigned at birth,

00:17:10.470 --> 00:17:12.480
really just get
all kinds of stuff.

00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:15.780
And Savannah is going to talk
a little bit about that and how

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:18.780
she's in an affirming
program now.

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:21.660
So, real quick, I
will just show you,

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:23.440
to kind of give you an idea.

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:25.740
So this is kind of a map--

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:28.359
is a map, actually--
of the United States

00:17:28.359 --> 00:17:31.650
and showing what states
have no protection.

00:17:31.650 --> 00:17:33.710
So you can see the red states--

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:35.880
so this is in the
child welfare system--

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:37.860
have no explicit
protections that

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:41.110
include sexual orientation,
gender identity, or expression.

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:42.189
Why is that important?

00:17:42.189 --> 00:17:43.980
Because if you're
working in these systems,

00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:45.479
if you're a
professional, say you're

00:17:45.479 --> 00:17:48.660
a staff at a group home
for kids in foster care,

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:51.600
and your training
says you may not

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:53.340
discriminate
against young people

00:17:53.340 --> 00:17:57.540
because our law or policy
says you can't, then you

00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:59.290
can get the message.

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:01.160
And it's clear.

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:04.070
If not, and somebody
says, you shouldn't

00:18:04.070 --> 00:18:06.922
be doing that, then you
could say, well, why?

00:18:06.922 --> 00:18:07.880
Where does it say that?

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:09.020
Right?

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:09.747
Nobody told me.

00:18:09.747 --> 00:18:11.330
Like, the law doesn't
say that, right?

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:14.810
So it just allows for people's
essential personal biases--

00:18:14.810 --> 00:18:16.590
beliefs-- to creep in.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:18.950
So I do a lot of work
around the country

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:20.872
of trying to make
sure that states

00:18:20.872 --> 00:18:22.580
do have explicit
protection and that they

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:26.234
do training to make
sure that people working

00:18:26.234 --> 00:18:27.650
with young people
in these systems

00:18:27.650 --> 00:18:31.400
understand that they
must treat young people--

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:33.590
must affirm their identity,
must treat them well,

00:18:33.590 --> 00:18:35.870
must make sure that they don't--

00:18:35.870 --> 00:18:37.910
they must not treat
them differently,

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:41.702
right, than non-LGBTQ
kids in their care.

00:18:41.702 --> 00:18:43.160
So that's the child
welfare system.

00:18:43.160 --> 00:18:47.221
And then you can see the
juvenile justice system.

00:18:47.221 --> 00:18:47.720
Right.

00:18:47.720 --> 00:18:51.560
If I can scroll down
just a little bit here.

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:52.672
Yeah.

00:18:52.672 --> 00:18:54.290
You get the idea.

00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:56.279
So we have a report
coming out soon

00:18:56.279 --> 00:18:58.820
with children's rights and the
Center for the Study of Social

00:18:58.820 --> 00:19:01.652
Policy that summarizes
all of this law, talks

00:19:01.652 --> 00:19:03.110
about the protections
in the state,

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:06.860
and also and really
importantly features providers

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:08.600
in the juvenile justice world--

00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:11.610
runaway and homeless youth
shelters, foster care--

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:14.180
that actually are affirming
transgender youth.

00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:16.940
So one of my clients
is now and Kate--

00:19:16.940 --> 00:19:18.920
and Savannah, too,
that you'll hear from--

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:20.580
are now on in
girls' programming.

00:19:20.580 --> 00:19:24.050
So as a transgender girl,
the state foster care agency

00:19:24.050 --> 00:19:27.260
has placed them in a girls'
group home, as they should,

00:19:27.260 --> 00:19:27.800
right?

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.174
So we're highlighting
people that

00:19:29.174 --> 00:19:31.460
are doing the right thing
as we know a lot of schools

00:19:31.460 --> 00:19:34.520
are, too, in affirming
young people.

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:37.460
And also having six
young people, who

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:39.080
are trans or
gender-nonconforming,

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:41.240
who are describing their
positive experiences,

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:43.700
because we hear so many
horror stories because a lot

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:45.026
of bad stuff is happening.

00:19:45.026 --> 00:19:46.400
But also really
important to know

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:48.380
that there are a lot of
people doing the right thing.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:50.760
And a lot of young people
that are benefiting from that.

00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:54.380
And so I will use
that as my segue over

00:19:54.380 --> 00:19:56.640
into hearing from some of them.

00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:01.070
So, Soul, you want
to come up first?

00:20:01.070 --> 00:20:05.440
So this is Savannah,
who lives in Pittsburgh.

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:08.988
And Lydia, you
want to say hello?

00:20:11.886 --> 00:20:13.270
LYDIA: Hello.

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:17.870
CURREY COOK: And this is Lydia,
who lives in San Antonio.

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:20.990
So I was talking a little
bit about focusing kind

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:23.882
of on youth in foster
care, juvenile justice,

00:20:23.882 --> 00:20:25.340
runaway and homeless
youth systems.

00:20:25.340 --> 00:20:29.330
But Soul, we actually
met because Soul

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:31.160
came to our attention
when we reached out

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:33.270
to the LGBT center
in New York City

00:20:33.270 --> 00:20:35.660
and were asking them about
whether they were seeing

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:38.930
undocumented LGBTQ
young people coming in

00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:40.850
and sort of what they
were doing about that.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:43.190
Like how were they
accessing legal help

00:20:43.190 --> 00:20:45.080
for those young people.

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:48.410
So maybe we'll start with Soul,
if you don't mind telling folks

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:50.690
a little bit about
where you're from

00:20:50.690 --> 00:20:53.320
and how you ended up in the US?

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:55.580
SOUL: Yeah, sure.

00:20:55.580 --> 00:20:57.380
Basically, my name is Soul.

00:20:57.380 --> 00:21:02.160
And I'm from West Africa.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:07.640
I moved out here in 2014.

00:21:07.640 --> 00:21:10.520
So, basically, I'm a student.

00:21:10.520 --> 00:21:16.100
And I'm part of LGBT people
[INAUDIBLE] community.

00:21:16.100 --> 00:21:23.260
So when I was in Africa, as
you know, like, in Africa,

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:25.100
LGBT people are--

00:21:25.100 --> 00:21:27.797
they don't have no
rights, you know?

00:21:27.797 --> 00:21:28.880
They don't have the right.

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:33.720
And it's a little bit hard
for us, for LGBT community,

00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:44.010
to defend themself over there,
and at the same time to--

00:21:44.010 --> 00:21:45.190
there is no right, you know?

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:51.630
And so, basically, I had
