00:39:16.775 --> 00:39:18.870
earlier about training
being critical, right?

00:39:18.870 --> 00:39:22.330
This is a good example of staff
doing this stuff that's clearly

00:39:22.330 --> 00:39:24.640
not good for young people.

00:39:24.640 --> 00:39:27.070
And, you know, and
Lydia actively getting

00:39:27.070 --> 00:39:28.540
hurt, right, as a part of it.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.120
So the good news
is that Lydia was

00:39:31.120 --> 00:39:35.050
able to get out of the halfway
house soon, back with her mom,

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:37.410
had a really affirming and
amazing parole officer,

00:39:37.410 --> 00:39:41.247
is off parole, working
now, and doing awesome.

00:39:41.247 --> 00:39:42.080
So that's good news.

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:46.210
So why don't we turn
and hear from Savannah.

00:39:46.210 --> 00:39:47.440
You ready?

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:48.570
Savannah?

00:39:48.570 --> 00:39:51.130
So why don't you tell
folks a little bit about--

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:54.202
you're in foster
care now, why don't

00:39:54.202 --> 00:39:56.530
you tell them a little
about where you are now,

00:39:56.530 --> 00:39:58.720
and how that is, and then
a little bit about how

00:39:58.720 --> 00:40:01.217
you got into care?

00:40:01.217 --> 00:40:02.050
SAVANNAH: All right.

00:40:02.050 --> 00:40:08.156
First I think we should give
Lydia and Soul some applause.

00:40:08.156 --> 00:40:11.558
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:13.990 --> 00:40:16.941
I was very moved by
both of your stories.

00:40:16.941 --> 00:40:18.190
So thank you for sharing them.

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:23.830
I am currently living
in what's called

00:40:23.830 --> 00:40:26.350
a supervised
independent living home.

00:40:29.210 --> 00:40:31.890
And it's a girls' home.

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:37.710
And all of the other youth
here have been very affirming.

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:39.900
And the staff has definitely
been very affirming.

00:40:39.900 --> 00:40:43.850
And it's a good place.

00:40:43.850 --> 00:40:47.230
I basically have my own
efficiency apartment.

00:40:47.230 --> 00:40:54.520
And it's basically
teaching us to-- it's kind

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:59.650
of like a halfway house from
leaving foster care going

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:04.040
into the real world, you
know, and becoming an adult.

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:09.190
And I think it's a
very good place for me.

00:41:09.190 --> 00:41:15.220
As far as how I got here, I was
living with my parents for--

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:17.540
I lived with them for 16 years.

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:21.910
And I was always very,
very close with my mom.

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:27.380
And I had a really
good childhood.

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:31.550
I am glad to say that I
have very good memories

00:41:31.550 --> 00:41:36.200
from my childhood.

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:43.900
And my mom always says
I was a wonderful child,

00:41:43.900 --> 00:41:46.510
a wonderful toddler
and child, and then

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:49.810
once I got to my
teenage years, that's

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:55.835
when things kind of started
to get a little bit shaky.

00:41:55.835 --> 00:41:58.090
I was going through
a lot of depression.

00:41:58.090 --> 00:42:05.700
And it was not entirely
because, but it

00:42:05.700 --> 00:42:09.720
had a lot to do
with, the fact that I

00:42:09.720 --> 00:42:14.160
felt as though I could not
come out as trans because I

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:18.640
knew around 14 or 15.

00:42:18.640 --> 00:42:22.220
And the thing is,
I couldn't come out

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:31.220
because my parents-- my dad
is a pastor at our church.

00:42:31.220 --> 00:42:40.950
And very, you know, I don't
want to say anti-LGBT,

00:42:40.950 --> 00:42:45.930
but not affirming
most definitely.

00:42:45.930 --> 00:42:54.110
And so eventually
it just kind of--

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:56.310
I just kind of blew up one day.

00:42:56.310 --> 00:43:04.900
And I actually had
come out to my parents

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:06.330
through a suicide note.

00:43:06.330 --> 00:43:09.460
So I was [INAUDIBLE] suicide.

00:43:09.460 --> 00:43:12.650
And then we went to counseling.

00:43:12.650 --> 00:43:14.660
And things started
to get better.

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:17.240
But they still
weren't affirming.

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:22.440
They knew, which was better
than before, I suppose, but they

00:43:22.440 --> 00:43:23.190
weren't affirming.

00:43:23.190 --> 00:43:26.760
So it wasn't a whole lot better.

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:33.870
And then one time--

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:35.470
yeah.

00:43:35.470 --> 00:43:38.140
It was soon after my
16th birthday, I think.

00:43:42.380 --> 00:44:00.300
I had ended up in a psych ward
because of suicidal ideations

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:02.580
because I was still
wasn't allowed to come out

00:44:02.580 --> 00:44:03.760
to anyone else, really.

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:09.431
And it's not--

00:44:09.431 --> 00:44:11.430
I guess it's not the
hardest thing in the world,

00:44:11.430 --> 00:44:17.540
but it's not easy to have
to hide all the time.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:25.110
And my first foster home
that I was placed in--

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:27.210
oh yeah, well, I
couldn't go back home.

00:44:27.210 --> 00:44:30.160
So I had to be placed
in foster care.

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:34.710
So the first foster home
that I was placed in

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:37.950
was definitely not affirming.

00:44:37.950 --> 00:44:40.540
And the agency wasn't affirming.

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:48.080
And it was-- once
again, I was closeted.

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:52.130
And I had to just go
to school as a boy

00:44:52.130 --> 00:44:54.470
and live my life as
a boy and, you know--

00:45:02.146 --> 00:45:03.520
first of all, it
wasn't pleasant.

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:07.540
But second, it was
entirely counterproductive.

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:09.160
The entire reason
that I was placed

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:14.440
in care in the first
place was because

00:45:14.440 --> 00:45:21.350
of problems at home relating
to my gender identity

00:45:21.350 --> 00:45:22.160
not being affirmed.

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:31.210
So I was removed from that
situation with my parents

00:45:31.210 --> 00:45:35.350
and put into an
identical situation.

00:45:35.350 --> 00:45:39.230
The only thing that's changed
is where I am and who I'm with.

00:45:39.230 --> 00:45:40.730
The situation
itself is the same.

00:45:40.730 --> 00:45:44.210
So it just wasn't--

00:45:48.690 --> 00:45:50.790
I don't think it
was a logical move.

00:45:50.790 --> 00:45:55.080
And then there
were other problems

00:45:55.080 --> 00:45:58.380
at that home entirely unrelated
to my gender identity.

00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:03.300
And, ultimately, I was
removed from that home

00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:04.554
for those reasons.

00:46:04.554 --> 00:46:06.970
And it didn't have anything
to do with my gender identity.

00:46:06.970 --> 00:46:09.330
But then I was
placed in a new home.

00:46:09.330 --> 00:46:10.830
They also weren't affirming.

00:46:10.830 --> 00:46:15.570
But I was allowed
to be out at school.

00:46:15.570 --> 00:46:28.100
I was allowed to express myself
through how I present myself,

00:46:28.100 --> 00:46:34.690
how I dress, my name and
pronouns, how I introduce

00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:37.195
myself to people, et cetera.

00:46:37.195 --> 00:46:38.570
CURREY COOK: And
Savannah, so you

00:46:38.570 --> 00:46:42.820
were at school in a pretty rural
area in Pennsylvania, right?

00:46:42.820 --> 00:46:43.840
SAVANNAH: Oh, yes.

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:44.350
Yeah.

00:46:44.350 --> 00:46:46.720
All three of these
placements my ho--

00:46:46.720 --> 00:46:47.286
I'm sorry?

00:46:47.286 --> 00:46:48.410
CURREY COOK: No, that's OK.

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:49.940
Go ahead.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:55.880
SAVANNAH: All three of
my placements-- my home,

00:46:55.880 --> 00:46:58.540
my first foster home, and
then this second foster home--

00:46:58.540 --> 00:47:02.500
they were all very rural areas.

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:13.020
And it's not that the people
at school weren't accepting.

00:47:13.020 --> 00:47:19.000
I think they just didn't know
how to react to it, I guess.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:19.650
I'm not sure.

00:47:19.650 --> 00:47:27.590
They had never-- transgender
people aren't exactly plentiful

00:47:27.590 --> 00:47:29.750
in schools such as that.

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:34.180
And not that there was any
stigma against people like me.

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:40.970
They just didn't know anything
about transgender people

00:47:40.970 --> 00:47:44.000
or the community.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:48.270
And they-- I feel like
I made a lot of people

00:47:48.270 --> 00:47:53.430
feel awkward just
by being there.

00:47:53.430 --> 00:47:54.762
It wasn't--

00:47:54.762 --> 00:47:55.720
CURREY COOK: I'm sorry.

00:47:55.720 --> 00:47:57.180
I remember you
telling me that it

00:47:57.180 --> 00:48:00.420
didn't seem like the people
running the foster care

00:48:00.420 --> 00:48:03.150
agencies and from the
county knew anything

00:48:03.150 --> 00:48:04.800
about working with
transgender youth

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:06.045
or had ever had any training

00:48:06.045 --> 00:48:08.710
SAVANNAH: Oh yeah,
they didn't either, no.

00:48:08.710 --> 00:48:12.310
CURREY COOK: And can you
tell everyone a little bit--

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:15.260
I know you had a particular
issue around clothing when

00:48:15.260 --> 00:48:17.070
you wanted to get clothing.

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:18.070
Do you want to tell us--

00:48:18.070 --> 00:48:21.010
SAVANNAH: Yeah.

00:48:21.010 --> 00:48:22.810
So, yes.

00:48:22.810 --> 00:48:26.650
The agency was
very non-affirming.

00:48:26.650 --> 00:48:35.070
And I can deal with
misgendering and calling me

00:48:35.070 --> 00:48:35.940
by the wrong name.

00:48:35.940 --> 00:48:38.970
I mean, people are going
to do that all the time.

00:48:38.970 --> 00:48:40.120
And my parents do that.

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:42.900
And I still love them to death.

00:48:42.900 --> 00:48:51.160
But, you know, Currey
talked in a slideshow

00:48:51.160 --> 00:49:01.845
about not discriminating
based on gender.

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:06.360
Like not even just
gender identity.

00:49:06.360 --> 00:49:09.380
Just on your biological sex.

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:12.710
I mean, they would--

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:18.530
OK, so they provide each child
a clothing allotment of--

00:49:18.530 --> 00:49:25.340
but it was some monthly
clothing allotment

00:49:25.340 --> 00:49:30.410
so we can go out and buy
clothing for ourselves to wear.

00:49:30.410 --> 00:49:35.220
And so it had to be--

00:49:35.220 --> 00:49:38.610
in the guidelines, it said
that you have the right

00:49:38.610 --> 00:49:45.810
to spend your clothing allotment
on gender-appropriate items

00:49:45.810 --> 00:49:46.470
of clothing.

00:49:46.470 --> 00:49:53.600
And so they restricted
me to only be

00:49:53.600 --> 00:49:55.490
allowed to buy boys' clothes.

00:49:55.490 --> 00:49:57.710
And, of course, you
know, the definition

00:49:57.710 --> 00:50:01.910
of what boys' clothes
are is arbitrary.

00:50:01.910 --> 00:50:09.160
But I guess what they
deemed to be boys' clothes

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:10.820
was all I was allowed to buy.

00:50:10.820 --> 00:50:12.020
So I ended up--

00:50:12.020 --> 00:50:17.355
before the first day of school,
I had to buy a new wardrobe.

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:22.330
$200 worth of clothes with--

00:50:22.330 --> 00:50:27.320
no, $280 something, actually,
of clothes with my own money

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:28.010
out of pocket.

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:31.400
And, of course, like it--

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:34.040
sometimes it sounds like--

00:50:34.040 --> 00:50:36.260
it's probably sounds
to some people

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:38.690
like it's really
not that big a deal.

00:50:38.690 --> 00:50:41.530
So they won't buy you
the clothes you want.

00:50:41.530 --> 00:50:49.850
But it's that they won't
buy me clothes that they

00:50:49.850 --> 00:50:51.460
would buy for another youth.

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:55.220
And they're doing it solely
based on my sex, what

00:50:55.220 --> 00:50:57.810
I was assigned at birth.

00:50:57.810 --> 00:51:01.550
CURREY COOK: Let me
pause you right there,

00:51:01.550 --> 00:51:04.210
because I think we want to
leave some time for questions.

00:51:04.210 --> 00:51:09.260
And then I just want to say that
this is when Savannah called

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:12.740
our help desk line because she
sort of knew, like, OK, this

00:51:12.740 --> 00:51:14.850
is clearly not right.

00:51:14.850 --> 00:51:16.330
You know?

00:51:16.330 --> 00:51:19.530
I don't know what the law
says, but this is not OK.

00:51:19.530 --> 00:51:22.100
And I think it really
puts a fine point on what

00:51:22.100 --> 00:51:23.160
we're talking about here.

00:51:23.160 --> 00:51:25.285
Like when you're in these
out-of-home care systems,

00:51:25.285 --> 00:51:27.450
the state controls
your whole life,

00:51:27.450 --> 00:51:30.266
including the clothes that
you wear, right, and can buy.

00:51:30.266 --> 00:51:31.265
So they were basically--

00:51:31.265 --> 00:51:32.480
[? LYDIA: ?] And
whether you're out.

00:51:32.480 --> 00:51:33.700
CURREY COOK: And
whether you're out.

00:51:33.700 --> 00:51:34.200
Right?

00:51:34.200 --> 00:51:36.780
So they were basically
saying, oh, by the way,

00:51:36.780 --> 00:51:39.450
gender is not defined anywhere.

00:51:39.450 --> 00:51:42.830
So we're just going to say
it's gender assigned at birth

00:51:42.830 --> 00:51:46.790
and deny a young person the
clothing that not only they

00:51:46.790 --> 00:51:51.020
want as a baseline, right, but
also that actually helps affirm

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:56.240
their identity, which drops all
of these awful outcomes, right?

00:51:56.240 --> 00:51:58.800
Suicidal ideation, depression,
and all this stuff.

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:01.790
And child welfare
agencies have to legally

00:52:01.790 --> 00:52:04.940
make sure you're safe,
they are responsible

00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:08.510
for your well-being, and
are going against everything

00:52:08.510 --> 00:52:11.540
that any professional standard
says about how you're supposed

00:52:11.540 --> 00:52:12.970
to respond to LGBT youth.

00:52:12.970 --> 00:52:18.270
So I think, you know, Lydia
and Savannah's examples

00:52:18.270 --> 00:52:21.640
really show, you know,
what a long way we

00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:24.979
have to go in these systems
to affirm trans youth

00:52:24.979 --> 00:52:27.270
and how they really bear the
brunt of all these things,

00:52:27.270 --> 00:52:28.490
right?

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:31.820
And the good news,
though, is that Savannah

00:52:31.820 --> 00:52:34.645
was affirmed in a school,
right, in rural Pennsylvania.

00:52:34.645 --> 00:52:36.770
And I think that's a good
takeaway with the Supreme

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:39.020
Court kicking the
Gavin Grimm case back

00:52:39.020 --> 00:52:42.680
down to the 4th Circuit
court of appeals.

00:52:42.680 --> 00:52:46.040
It still may be a bit before we
get these issues to the Supreme

00:52:46.040 --> 00:52:46.640
Court.

00:52:46.640 --> 00:52:48.830
Could be a good thing,
may be a bad thing,

00:52:48.830 --> 00:52:50.840
depending on the makeup
of the Supreme Court.

00:52:50.840 --> 00:52:52.340
But in the meantime,
there are a lot

00:52:52.340 --> 00:52:54.089
of schools that are
doing the right thing.

00:52:54.089 --> 00:52:56.060
And I think hearing
their positive stories is

00:52:56.060 --> 00:52:58.220
a good reminder to us
of the good stuff that's

00:52:58.220 --> 00:52:59.480
going on out there, too.

00:52:59.480 --> 00:53:01.370
So I'll turn it over
to Alex now and see

00:53:01.370 --> 00:53:02.979
if anybody has questions.

00:53:02.979 --> 00:53:06.262
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:07.925 --> 00:53:10.050
ALEX: The question was,
what is your interpretation

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:12.682
of the recent decision not
to hear the Gavin Grimm case?

00:53:12.682 --> 00:53:14.640
What does it mean in
general for interpretation

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:16.690
that transgender people
are protected by sex

00:53:16.690 --> 00:53:18.610
anti-discrimination laws?

00:53:18.610 --> 00:53:21.630
CURREY COOK: So you all may have
followed that during the Obama

00:53:21.630 --> 00:53:23.790
administration, the
Department of Justice

00:53:23.790 --> 00:53:27.120
issued these guidelines to
the school district saying,

00:53:27.120 --> 00:53:30.000
basically, Title IX, which
protects against discrimination

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.280
in schools based
on sex, that that

00:53:32.280 --> 00:53:35.700
means you should
comply with the law,

00:53:35.700 --> 00:53:39.080
affirm transgender
students at school.

00:53:39.080 --> 00:53:42.192
And so the case that the
ACLU had with Gavin Grimm

00:53:42.192 --> 00:53:43.650
sort of wound up
through the courts

00:53:43.650 --> 00:53:46.110
and then the appellate
court basically

00:53:46.110 --> 00:53:48.630
decided on that guidance.

00:53:48.630 --> 00:53:51.810
And so then, as the Supreme
Court was considering

00:53:51.810 --> 00:53:55.650
what to do with it, and it was
scheduled for oral argument,

00:53:55.650 --> 00:53:58.500
the Trump administration
rescinded that guidance

00:53:58.500 --> 00:54:03.270
and basically said, states, do
what you want, whatever, right?

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:04.837
Don't bully
transgender students.

00:54:04.837 --> 00:54:06.420
But oh, by the way,
you don't actually

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:08.460
have to affirm their identity.

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:10.800
Which, of course, you can't
have both of those things

00:54:10.800 --> 00:54:12.660
at the same time.

00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:14.820
But the Supreme Court
then said, all right,

00:54:14.820 --> 00:54:17.089
well, we're actually just
going to-- if this was based

00:54:17.089 --> 00:54:19.380
on the guidance and the Trump
administration pulled it,

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:21.120
we're just going to
kick this back down

00:54:21.120 --> 00:54:23.140
to the appellate
court to decide it.

00:54:23.140 --> 00:54:24.600
And that's kind of
where it is now.

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:26.397
So they're going to
be deciding again.

00:54:26.397 --> 00:54:28.230
That could result in a
really good decision,

00:54:28.230 --> 00:54:31.050
as most courts
have said Title IX,

00:54:31.050 --> 00:54:33.540
the sex protection means
you can't discriminate

00:54:33.540 --> 00:54:34.930
based on gender identity.

00:54:34.930 --> 00:54:37.170
But obviously we're
worried about who's

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:39.660
going to be on
the Supreme Court.

00:54:39.660 --> 00:54:43.200
And so if another
justice or two drops off

00:54:43.200 --> 00:54:44.700
and we have a
conservative majority,

00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:47.190
that could be really
bad for a decision

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:49.930
like that one going back up.

00:54:49.930 --> 00:54:53.190
ALEX: I wanted to ask
Soul specifically,

00:54:53.190 --> 00:54:56.090
with kind of the new
administration and this focus

00:54:56.090 --> 00:54:58.590
on immigration-- this is such
an issue we were hearing about

00:54:58.590 --> 00:55:00.990
