01:00:03.016 --> 01:00:04.390
generally, in
immigration courts.

01:00:04.390 --> 01:00:07.820
Like another client of
mine who's from Ghana,

01:00:07.820 --> 01:00:13.289
he just literally just missed--
you know, fled for his life,

01:00:13.289 --> 01:00:14.330
just missed being killed.

01:00:14.330 --> 01:00:16.160
A friend of his was
murdered who was gay.

01:00:16.160 --> 01:00:20.540
And managed to get out all
the way through Latin America,

01:00:20.540 --> 01:00:22.360
declared asylum at
the Mexican border,

01:00:22.360 --> 01:00:24.230
was placed in detention
for seven months,

01:00:24.230 --> 01:00:26.900
and ended up being released to
a family friend in the Bronx.

01:00:26.900 --> 01:00:31.730
But his asylum case, the hearing
is set for November 2019.

01:00:31.730 --> 01:00:33.440
This was like a year ago, right?

01:00:33.440 --> 01:00:36.650
So in the meantime, he was
just sort of here in limbo.

01:00:36.650 --> 01:00:39.080
We helped him get Special
Immigrant Juvenile Status, too,

01:00:39.080 --> 01:00:41.390
because that's actually
something he was eligible for,

01:00:41.390 --> 01:00:41.890
right?

01:00:41.890 --> 01:00:44.330
So just in general,
it's just a mess.

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:45.634
A long time to wait.

01:00:45.634 --> 01:00:47.300
And I think now,
particularly for people

01:00:47.300 --> 01:00:49.300
who are in the
administrative process--

01:00:49.300 --> 01:00:51.860
so they aren't in deportation
proceedings but they are

01:00:51.860 --> 01:00:54.980
actually going to be going in
front of asylum officers who

01:00:54.980 --> 01:00:58.100
